    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Cinchona pubescens are derived from its bark, which contains quinine and other alkaloids. Cinchona tincture is a concentrated liquid extract of the bark, typically made with ethanol or glycerin, and is used to treat fever, malaria, and other conditions. Cinchona extract is a powdered or liquid form of the bark's active compounds, often standardized to contain a specific amount of quinine or other alkaloids. Cinchona infusion and cinchona tea are decoctions made by steeping the bark in hot water, releasing its bioactive compounds, while cinchona bark tea is a specific type of infusion made from the dried and crushed bark, traditionally used in folk medicine to treat fever and other ailments. These preparations are valued for their anti-inflammatory, antipyretic, and antimicrobial properties, making them useful for treating a range of health conditions.",
