    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Cinchona pubescens improperly include exacerbating malaria due to its antimalarial properties being disrupted, leading to hypotension as the heart rate and blood pressure decrease, causing nausea and vomiting due to the bitter and toxic compounds found in the plant, and potentially causing cardiac arrest from the excessive decrease in blood pressure, which is a result of the plant's toxic alkaloids, specifically quinine and quinidine, reacting with the body's cardiovascular system. Cinchona pubescens contains toxic compounds that can have adverse effects on the body when consumed in excess or improperly, leading to a range of side effects. The improper use of this plant can disrupt its intended therapeutic effects, making it a potentially hazardous substance when not used under medical supervision. The high levels of toxic alkaloids in Cinchona pubescens can lead to cardiac arrest, hypotension, and nausea when ingested in excess. This is why it is essential to use Cinchona pubescens under the guidance of a medical professional to avoid these potentially life-threatening side effects."
